{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529826"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.07,0.11,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41083"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4021"},{"type":"tags","id":"4023"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43530"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with palpitations and chest discomfort. He has metastatic non-small cell lung cancer and is not receiving active management. His medical history includes ischaemic heart disease with coronary stents, stage 4 chronic kidney disease, and hypertension. He does not take any regular medications other than Aspirin, following a recent review by a palliative care physician. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears comfortable. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 132/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is mild peripheral oedema and dullness to percussion at the right lung base consistent with a pleural effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 6.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum magnesium: 0.5 mmol/L (0.7-1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 19 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETroponin I: 15 ng/L (\u0026lt;26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows tall, peaked T waves and a prolonged PR interval.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral sodium polystyrene sulfonate","Intravenous furosemide","Urgent haemodialysis","Intravenous insulin and glucose","Intravenous calcium gluconate"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with palpitations and ECG changes consistent with hyperkalaemia (tall, peaked T waves and prolonged PR interval) in the context of a high serum potassium (6.2 mmol/L) and hypomagnesaemia (0.5 mmol/L). Despite his palliative status due to metastatic non-small cell lung cancer, the most appropriate next step in management is to administer \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous calcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because hyperkalaemia with ECG changes and cardiac symptoms (palpitations) requires immediate treatment to prevent potentially life-threatening arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous calcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for hyperkalaemia with ECG changes or symptoms. It acts rapidly to stabilise cardiac cell membranes, reducing the risk of arrhythmias. This treatment is appropriate even in palliative patients as it addresses an acute, potentially distressing symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous insulin and glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is often used as a second-line treatment for hyperkalaemia. It works by shifting potassium into cells, lowering serum levels. However, it is not the first step when there are ECG changes and cardiac symptoms, as its onset of action is slower than calcium gluconate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium polystyrene sulfonate (Resonium A)\u003C/strong\u003E is a potassium-binding resin that can be used for less urgent treatment of hyperkalaemia. It has a slow onset of action and would not be appropriate as the first-line treatment for a patient with ECG changes and cardiac symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E can help reduce potassium levels by increasing renal excretion. However, given this patient\u0027s severely impaired renal function (eGFR 19 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2), it is unlikely to be effective and would not be the most appropriate first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for severe hyperkalaemia, especially in patients with renal failure. However, it is an invasive procedure that may not align with the patient\u0027s goals of care given his palliative status. It would be considered only if less invasive measures fail to control his symptoms and potassium levels, and if it aligns with his wishes and overall care plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s also important to note the patient\u0027s hypomagnesaemia, which can exacerbate the cardiac effects of hyperkalaemia. After initial stabilisation with calcium gluconate, addressing the magnesium deficiency would be an important next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing this patient, it\u0027s crucial to balance immediate safety (treating the hyperkalaemia) with overall goals of care for a patient with advanced cancer. After initial stabilisation, a discussion about goals of care and future management of renal dysfunction would be appropriate. The normal troponin level suggests that the patient\u0027s symptoms are likely due to hyperkalaemia rather than an acute coronary syndrome, further supporting the priority of treating the electrolyte disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium gluconate is the first-line treatment for hyperkalaemia with ECG changes or symptoms, even in palliative patients.","Hyperkalaemia management in patients with advanced cancer should balance immediate safety with overall goals of care.","Hypomagnesaemia can exacerbate cardiac effects of hyperkalaemia and should be corrected concurrently.","Treatment for eminently reversible conditions should always be considered even for patients with advanced metastatic cancer"],"references":["Emergency Care Institute, Agency for Clinical Innovation, NSW Health. Potassium \u2013 hyperkalaemia. Available online ; https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/electrolytes/potassium-hyperkalaemia","Western Australia Country Health Service (WACHS). Hyperkalaemia Guideline 2024. Available online at ; https://www.wacountry.health.wa.gov.au/~/media/WACHS/Documents/About-us/Policies/Hyperkalaemia-Guideline.pdf?thn=0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41083"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41083"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T16:49:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T16:51:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55543"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/197"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hyperkalaemia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09